node.text:
Welcome to our second episode of Flat Hats @ Home! Bringing you a slice of RNSP to your home. 
Redwoods seeds rarely become mature, giant redwoods... so how has the redwood species survived for millenniums?

Join us as we take you into the redwood forest to uncover the amazing, unique way redwoods reproduce- without seeds! If the forest family tree doesn't shock you - the size and complexity of the redwoods in this video sure will!

#redwoodnps #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque #FindYourVirtualPark

node.text:
Learn about redwood reproduction with Ranger Ally in our first episode of Flat Hats @ Home brought to you by Redwood National and State Parks! 
#redwoodnps #findyourvirtualpark #findyourpark #encuentratuparque

With less foot traffic in our parks, we are seeing wildlife reclaiming the landscape! One of camp hosts at RNSP witnessed two Roosevelt bull elk practicing sparring with their antlers on a park sign. Not shown in this video is the sign completely removed from its post! 
#Findyourvirtualpark #NationalParkWeek #EncuentraTuParque #RNSP [Video description: Two Roosevelt Bull elk sparring antlers on a park sign.]

node.title: Roosevelt Bull Elk Take Down Sign

node.accessibility_caption: An upward view of a hollow scorched redwood tree. The tree appears to be standing magically as there are only small pieces of wood holding it up.

node.text:
“Blessed are they who see beautiful things in humble places where other people see nothing.” - Camille Pissarro, painter

Many visitors only want to see the biggest or tallest trees, which is great! But as park rangers, we also aim to share the humbled dignity of each trail within the redwood forest. Each tree, big or small, is undoubtedly beautiful and unique. 

The Hope Creek and Ten Taypo Loop Trail offers a glimpse into the true majesty of the old-growth forest. The coast redwoods along the trail have been scarred and scorched from centuries of existence. Their complex structures create a living tapestry of resilience while dense vegetation create a kaleidoscope of green color. The top of the trail, an old dirt road, offers a unique view of a young Douglas-fir forest and serves as a stark contrast to the redwood forest you travel through. Have you seen beautiful trees on the #TrailsLessTraveled within the park? 

The Hope Creek and Ten Taypo Loop Trail can be found at the north end of Prairie Creek Redwoods State Parks and is 3.6 miles round-trip. The trail is rated as moderate and climbs just over 700 feet total. We suggest that you hike the trail counterclockwise to avoid a steeper, more difficult hike. Bring some trekking poles and water on this hike, because it often gets a little warm and can be slippery in the morning. 

Whether you are looking for a short walk or a long hike, any trail within the park is bound to leave you breathless. In this #TrailsLessTraveledTuesday series, we aim to showcase some of the less visited but vastly scenic trails within the parks.

Photos courtesy Dave Van de Mark

node.text:
Due to the rampant increase of the highly infectious new Delta variant of COVID-19, updated CDC guidelines require all visitors and park staff to wear masks while inside park buildings, including all visitor centers. 

You must wear a mask even if you are fully vaccinated. The latest evidence shows fully vaccinated people can still carry and infect those who are not yet fully vaccinated.  Please also wear a mask when outdoors, if you cannot maintain a distance of six feet apart. Your compliance with these guidelines will help ensure that all of our visitors will stay healthy and continue to enjoy their time in the parks and abroad. Thank you!

[Image description: An painted illustration of an antlered elk wearing a face mask in front of a woodland prairie backdrop in a wood grain-patterned frame with texts reading, "Cover your snout, when you go out! Stay healthy. Stay smart. Hike six feet apart."]

[NPS Illustration: S. Krause]

node.text:
Looking for a great challenge-by-choice hike or bike ride? Maybe a fantastic picnic area? Look no further than Lost Man Creek!

This is one of Ranger Mark’s favorite #TrailsLessTraveled because it offers great out-and-back hiking, biking opportunities, and a splendid picnic location within old-growth redwood trees. Lost Man Creek is a great destination for any visitor, hiker or biker looking for some solitude.

Out for a hike? From the Lost Man Creek parking lot and picnic area, you can hike to the 3rd bridge for a nice 2-mile round-trip hike within some big trees. You only have to make it  ¼-mile down the trail to visit site where Redwood National and State Parks was formally designated as a United Nations World Heritage Site in 1980. If you are looking for a more vigorous stroll, hike further into second-growth forest and climb up to Holter Ridge for a one-way 11-mile hike with a turn-around at Bald Hills Road.

Out for a bike ride? Lost Man Creek Picnic Area is at the end of the Davison bike trail. You can access the bike path from Elk Meadow Day Use Area, the Elk Prairie Campground, or the Prairie Creek Visitor Center. A biking adventure from Prairie Creek Visitor Center to Lost Man Creek and back is about 12 miles of scenic biking on a gravel/dirt path. If you are looking for a more strenuous bike ride, you park at the Lost Man Creek parking lot and create a 22-mile ride by biking up and down the trail with a turn-around at Bald Hills Road. 

Want to learn more about Lost Man Creek? https://www.nps.gov/places/lostmancreektrail.htm 

Whether you are looking for a short walk or a long hike, any trail within the park is bound to leave you breathless. In this #TrailsLessTraveledTuesday series, we aim to showcase some of the less visited but vastly scenic trails within the park. 

Photos courtesy Dave Van de Mark

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Redwood N&S Parks on July 20, 2021. May be an image of tree, sky, nature, mountain and grass.

node.text:
“The prairie has a stronger hold on the senses” – Albert Pike, poet

The hike to Lyon’s Ranch is a favorite among the redwood rangers. Vastly different than many other hikes within the park, it offers a tour of the senses that cannot be replicated. Situated above the fog line, you can feel the sunlight on your skin. You can taste the sweet juice of a blackberry or apple in the fall. You can smell the fragrance of lupine drifting in spring air. You can hear the wind rustling the prairie grasses and the sound of ruffed grouse drumming in the distance. And finally, you can look out onto the wide-open expanse of the redwood creek watershed and experience over a century of history. 

The Lyons Ranch Trailhead is situated 17 miles from Highway 101 on Bald Hills Road. The 4.5-mile round-trip trail takes you downhill about 750 feet on a beautiful gravel road. At the end of the road, the barn and bunkhouses allow hikers to step back in time as they step into the preserved buildings. Each season offers a different hiking experience from prancing through wildflowers in the spring to wildlife viewing in the fall and finally snowshoeing in the winter. 

Whether you are looking for a short walk or a long hike, any trail within the park is bound to leave you breathless. In this #TrailsLessTraveledTuesday series, we aim to showcase some of the less visited but vastly scenic trails within the parks.

node.text:
“Leave the roads, take the trails” – Pythagoras

Any park ranger will encourage you to step into the redwood forest. Ranger Serena would send you to Nature Trail, one of her favorite walks in the park. The old-growth redwoods tower over your head and the blanket of ferns around you display more shades of green than imaginable. Ranger Serena loves this trail for its old-growth redwoods, its seasonal river crossing, its quiet atmosphere, and its ease of access. 

Want to hike the Nature Trail? The ‘Nature Trail’ 1-mile loop trail begins and ends at the Prairie Creek Visitor Center. With less than 110 feet of elevation gain, this trail is great for families and any visitor looking for a short hike in big trees. You may even find Ranger Serena peering into the forest canopy. 

Whether you are looking for a short walk or a long hike, any trail within the park is bound to leave you breathless. In this #TrailsLessTraveledTuesday series, we aim to showcase some of the less visited but vastly scenic trails within the parks.

node.text:
Talk about cramped conditions! Can you imagine sharing a small space with 3 siblings? 

If you are driving around the country with your family or stuck inside because of hot weather, you might be feeling crammed! Just like these barn swallows! 

If you are looking for some feathery friends, look no further than Kuchel Visitor Center! Barns swallows, a popular and common bird around North America, come back every year to nest on the rafters of our building. Around the fall, they will head back to their winter grounds in Central and South America! 

For the time being, we love to hear their chirps, watch them fledge (begin to fly), and dodge their droppings! 

Do you see barn swallows where you live?

node.text:
Are you heading this way for the holiday weekend? 🇺🇸 

Lots of people are doing the same! Check out our ‘Top Ten Ranger Tips’ highlighted as a saved story to help your trip go as smooth as possible. Expect full parking lots at trailheads and lines at the visitor center! 

Remember to plan ahead for camping and hiking. All campgrounds are reserved and full for the peak summer months. Backcountry camping permits and Tall Trees trail permits are both reserved and full for the upcoming weekend.

NPS Photo | Dave Van de Mark

node.accessibility_caption: A very cute black bear cub clings to a tree

node.text:
We can bear-ly believe it’s already almost 4th of July weekend! So today for #WildlifeWednesday, we want to remind you to be bear aware! 🐻

You can keep our wildlife and visitors safe by remembering to… 
🐻 If you see a black bear, do not panic! Make noise and make yourself look as big as possible. Speak to the bear with a calm voice and make it clear that you are human. 
🐻 When camping, store all food, coolers and smelly items in food lockers. This is SUPER important! Practicing safe food storage insures the safety for both our wildlife and you! 
🐻  Stay a safe distance from bears (and all wildlife). Never approach! 

Have you seen a bear at Redwood National & State Parks? 

NPS Photo | Steven Krause

#RecreateResponsibly #WildlifeWednesday

node.accessibility_caption: A black and yellow butterfly perches on a white flower. Redwoods can be seen in the background.

node.text:
Happy National Pollinator Week! 🦋 

Here in Redwood National and State Parks we have many different pollinators that help to keep our forest ecosystems healthy. Featured here is a Western Tiger Swallowtail. 

What’s a pollinator? 
A pollinator is an organism that helps to transfer the pollen grains from one flower to another. This process allows for the fertilization of flowers so they may produce fruits and seeds. 

Here in Redwood National and State Parks we have many plants that rely on pollinators to fertilize them so they can produce their wild berries. These berries, like salmonberry, huckleberry, and blackberries, are a critical food source for many animals. Without the help of pollinators, plants would not be able to flower and produce the seeds for next year’s plants. 

Check out the Redwood Creek Trail if you want to see some pollinators at work on your trip in Redwood National and State Parks!

NPS Photo | M. Hassett

node.accessibility_caption: Fog forms over False Klamath Cove. Yellow flowers stand in the foreground. Sea stacks litter the blue ocean. The sky is blue and pink.

node.text:
We appreciate you, Pacific Ocean! 🌊 

We might be a day late for #WorldOceansDay but we still wanted to give that big, blue, and beautiful ocean a shout-out.

The Pacific Ocean plays a vital role in the health of the ecosystems here at Redwood. Not only does it provide a habitat to hundreds of flora and fauna, it creates the coastal climate that allows our forests and prairies to thrive. 

#WorldOceansDay reminds us of the vital role oceans play in our everyday lives. They give us oxygen, absorb carbon dioxide, create jobs, give us amazing views, and support the Earth’s ecosystems. 

Whether you are a coastal dweller or cherishing the ocean from afar, think of our oceans and give them a little wave of appreciation! 🌊

Photo courtesy of Dave Van de Mark

node.text:
Happy #PRIDE Month! 

Redwood National and State Parks is a forest for all! 

#pridemonth #forestforall #loveislove

[Video: cartoon redwoods with a changing rainbow background ]

node.accessibility_caption: Yellow beams of sunshine shine through the redwood forest canopy.

node.text:
Today and forever we will remember our fallen heroes. We remember their sacrifice and the light they brought to our lives. 

The scientific name for the coast redwood is 𝘚𝘦𝘲𝘶𝘰𝘪𝘢 𝘴𝘦𝘮𝘱𝘦𝘳𝘷𝘪𝘳𝘦𝘯𝘴 which means everlasting. Our memory of our fallen heroes is the same. 

Have a great Memorial Day! 🇺🇸

NPS Photo | G. Craig 

#MemorialDay #findyourpark #encuentratuparque
